  "text": "This analysis identifies the key source files implementing AddressSanitizer (ASan) instrumentation in both LLVM and GCC compilers.\n\n## LLVM Implementation (llvm/llvm-project)\n\n### 1. ASan Interceptors (compiler-rt/lib/asan/asan_interceptors.cpp)\nThis file contains the implementation of ASan interceptors for standard library functions. The file is documented as 'a part of AddressSanitizer' and intercepts various libc functions to monitor memory access. It defines interceptor wrappers in the __asan namespace that wrap standard library calls like malloc, free, memcpy, strcpy, and other libc functions.\n\n### 2. ASan Runtime Initialization (compiler-rt/lib/asan/asan_rtl.cpp)\nThis is the main runtime library file for ASan, documented as 'Main file of the ASan run-time library.' It handles the runtime initialization and coordination of ASan, with the key class AsanInitializer managing startup and initialization procedures. This file orchestrates the ASan runtime environment, memory mapping, and initialization of various ASan components.\n\n### 3. LLVM IR Instrumentation Pass (llvm/lib/Transforms/Instrumentation/AddressSanitizer.cpp)\nThis file implements the core LLVM pass for ASan instrumentation at the IR level. The primary struct AddressSanitizer is responsible for transforming LLVM IR code to insert shadow memory checks and instrumentation. This is where ASan checks are inserted into the code before compilation, including memory access checks that detect out-of-bounds and use-after-free bugs at runtime.\n\n## GCC Implementation (gcc-mirror/gcc)\n\n### 4. ASan Implementation (gcc/asan.cc)\nThis file implements AddressSanitizer as a GCC pass, documented as 'AddressSanitizer, a fast memory error detector.' It contains the main optimization pass implementations via two key classes:\n- pass_asan: The standard ASan pass for instrumented builds\n- pass_asan_O0: The ASan pass for unoptimized builds (O0 level)\n\nThe file also includes the asan_redzone_buffer class for managing shadow memory redzone buffers and various instrumentation functions like asan_shadow_offset(), asan_mark_p(), and other core ASan functionality.\n\n### 5. ASan Header (gcc/asan.h)\nThis header file provides the public interface for ASan functionality in GCC, exposing key functions like asan_function_start(), asan_finish_file(), asan_emit_stack_protection(), asan_expand_check_ifn(), and asan_expand_mark_ifn(). It defines the contract between the ASan pass and other GCC components.\n\n## Summary\nBoth compilers implement ASan through instrumentation passes that insert runtime checks into user code. LLVM performs instrumentation at the IR level through the AddressSanitizer pass before lowering to machine code, while GCC implements it as tree-based and RTL-based passes. Both maintain interceptor libraries to monitor standard library functions and coordinate shadow memory management for detecting memory errors at runtime."
}

